Practical No. 7: Raise Issue in GitHub

Aim
To raise an issue in a GitHub repository and resolve it using a pull request.

Procedure
1. Open your web browser and go to https://github.com and login to your GitHub account.

2. Open the repository where you want to raise the issue.

3. Click on the 'Issues' tab in the repository.

4. Click on the 'New Issue' button.

5. Enter the issue title and description explaining the problem.

6. Click on 'Submit new issue' to create the issue.

7. If working in a group, you can assign the issue to a team member.

8. Open Git Bash and clone the repository using the command: git clone https://github.com/username/repository-name.git

9. Move into the project directory using the command: cd repository-name

10. Create a new branch to fix the issue using the command: git branch fix-issue

11. Switch to the new branch using the command: git checkout fix-issue

12. Open the required file (for example index.html) and make necessary changes.

13. Add the modified files using the command: git add .

14. Commit the changes using the command: git commit -m 'Update index.html with necessary changes'

15. Push the branch to GitHub using the command: git push origin fix-issue

16. Open the repository on GitHub and click on 'Compare & Pull Request'.

17. Add a title and description for the pull request.

18. Click on 'Create Pull Request'.

19. Review the pull request and click on 'Merge Pull Request'.

20. Click on 'Confirm Merge' to merge the changes.

21. Finally go back to the Issues tab and close the issue if it is resolved.

Result
The issue was successfully created in GitHub and resolved using a pull request.
